      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Send a narrow X-ray beam into a target and inspect radiation scattered through ninety degrees. Alongside the original wavelength, a second peak appears at a wavelength about 2.43 picometers longer.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.2,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:47:43"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "Classical wave scattering predicts that a driven electron reradiates at the incident frequency. Why does part of the scattered beam come back red-shifted instead?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.49,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:47:43"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "In the classical picture, the incoming electric field shakes the electron. The electron radiates at that same driving frequency, so the outgoing wavelength should equal the incoming wavelength.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.26,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:47:43"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Compton treated the X-ray as a photon with energy h c over lambda and momentum h over lambda. It collides with an electron, which carries away energy and momentum as recoil.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "collide"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.37,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:47:43"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 5,
      "narration_text": "The wavelength increase is the photon's energy loss made visible.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 4.31,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:47:43"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Before the collision, the photon carries momentum h over lambda along one direction. Afterward, the photon leaves at angle theta and the electron recoils so the two outgoing momentum vectors still add to the original.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "vectors"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.97,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:47:43"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Solving the energy and momentum balance gives delta lambda equals h over electron mass c, times one minus cosine theta. The prefactor is the electron Compton wavelength.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.77,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:47:43"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "At zero degrees, cosine theta is one and the shift is zero. At ninety degrees, the shift is one Compton wavelength: 2.426 picometers.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.92,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:47:43"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "At one hundred eighty degrees, the photon reverses direction. The shift reaches its maximum, two Compton wavelengths, or 4.853 picometers.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "reverse"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.83,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:47:43"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Plot the shift against angle and it follows one minus cosine theta: zero forward, one unit sideways, two units backward. The target material does not set this free-electron kinematic scale.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.8,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:47:43"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "The longer wavelength is recoil bookkeeping. A photon gives energy and momentum to an electron, so the photon must leave with less energy and less momentum.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.05,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B12.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:47:43"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Your turn. What shift does the formula predict at sixty degrees? Express the answer first in Compton wavelengths, then in picometers.",
